05354nam a22007215i 9780812202984DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20102003pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979748170  a97808122029847 a10.9783/97808122029842doi  a(DE-B1597)449155  a(OCoLC)759158280  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823.9121 aNorris, Margot, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSuspicious Readings of Joyce's "Dubliners" /cMargot Norris. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2010] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Gnomon of the Book: “The Sisters” -- t2 A Walk on the Wild(e) Side: “An Encounter” -- t3 Blind Streets and Seeing Houses: “Araby” -- t4 The Perils of “Eveline” -- t5 Masculinity Games in “After the Race” -- t6 Gambling with Gambles in “Two Gallants” -- t7 Narrative Bread Pudding: “The Boarding House” -- t8 Men Under a Cloud in “A Little Cloud” -- t9 Farrington, the Scrivener, Revisited: “Counterparts” -- t10 Narration Under the Blindfold in “Clay” -- t11 Shocking the Reader in “A Painful Case” -- t12 Genres in Dispute: “Ivy Day in the Committee Room” -- t13 Critical Judgment and Gender Prejudice in “A Mother” -- t14 Setting Critical Accounts Aright in “Grace” -- t15 The Politics of Gender and Art in “The Dead” -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBecause the stories in James Joyce's Dubliners seem to function as models of fiction, they are able to stand in for fiction in general in their ability to make the operation of texts explicit and visible. Joyce's stories do this by provoking skepticism in the face of their storytelling. Their narrative unreliabilities—produced by strange gaps, omitted scenes, and misleading narrative prompts—arouse suspicion and oblige the reader to distrust how and why the story is told.As a result, one is prompted to look into what is concealed, omitted, or left unspoken, a quest that often produces interpretations in conflict with what the narrative surface suggests about characters and events. Margot Norris's strategy in her analysis of the stories in Dubliners is to refuse to take the narrative voice for granted and to assume that every authorial decision to include or exclude, or to represent in a particular way, may be read as motivated. Suspicious Readings of Joyce's Dubliners examines the text for counterindictions and draws on the social context of the writing in order to offer readings from diverse theoretical perspectives.Suspicious Readings of Joyce's Dubliners devotes a chapter to each of the fifteen stories in Dubliners and shows how each confronts the reader with an interpretive challenge and an intellectual adventure. Its readings of "An Encounter," "Two Gallants," "A Painful Case," "A Mother," "The Boarding House," and "Grace" reconceive the stories in wholly novel ways—ways that reveal Joyce's writing to be even more brilliant, more exciting, and more seriously attuned to moral and political issues than we had thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9